etrial thickness (in millimetres) at the start and end of the proliferative phase?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["2-4 to 10-14","1-2 to 4-6","5-7 to 15-20","3-5 to 8-10","8-10 to 18-22"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring the proliferative (follicular) phase of the menstrual cycle, the endometrium grows under the influence of oestrogen produced by developing ovarian follicles. The endometrium starts at \u003Cstrong\u003E2-4 mm\u003C/strong\u003E thickness following menstruation. It then proliferates to reach \u003Cstrong\u003E10-14 mm\u003C/strong\u003E by the time of ovulation to prepare for potential implantation. The other suggested measurements are incorrect - \u003Cstrong\u003E1-2 to 4-6 mm\u003C/strong\u003E is too thin throughout, \u003Cstrong\u003E5-7 to 15-20 mm\u003C/strong\u003E starts too thick, \u003Cstrong\u003E3-5 to 8-10 mm\u003C/strong\u003E shows insufficient growth, and \u003Cstrong\u003E8-10 to 18-22 mm\u003C/strong\u003E represents excessive thickness.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The endometrium grows from 2-4 mm to 10-14 mm during the proliferative phase of the menstrual cycle.","Endometrial proliferation is driven by rising oestrogen levels from the developing follicle."],"references":["Hawkins SM, Matzuk MM. The menstrual cycle: basic biology. Ann N Y Acad Sci. 2008;1135:10-8. doi: 10.1196/annals.1429.018. PMID: 18574203; PMCID: PMC2913133","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection 